🚀 GitOps-Based Deployment Overview

This project follows the GitOps methodology, a modern approach to managing infrastructure and application deployments using Git as the single source of truth

📌 What is GitOps?

GitOps is a practice where all infrastructure and application configurations are defined declaratively and stored in a Git repository. Instead of manually applying changes to the system, updates are made through Git commits, ensuring consistency, traceability, and version control

⚙️ How It Works
Application and infrastructure configurations are written as declarative YAML manifests
These manifests are stored and versioned in a Git repository
A GitOps controller continuously monitors the repository
Whenever changes are pushed, the controller automatically applies them to the system
It also ensures that the actual system state always matches the desired state defined in Git

🧩 Core Principles
1. Declarative Configuration
The entire system state is defined using declarative files

2. Version Control
Every change is tracked in Git, providing a complete history and audit trail

3.Automated Deployment (Pull-Based)
Changes are automatically pulled and applied by the system

4. Continuous Reconciliation
The system constantly checks and corrects any drift between actual and desired states

🎯 Benefits
Improved Security – Eliminates unauthorized manual changes
Traceability – Full history of changes through Git commits
Consistency – Ensures environments remain identical
Auto-Healing – Automatically fixes configuration drift
Simplified Rollbacks – Easily revert to previous stable states

🌍 Use Case
This approach is particularly effective for managing containerized applications and infrastructure, especially in Kubernetes environments, but the core principles can be applied to other systems as well